Title: Loop (Ring, #3)
Author: Kōji Suzuki
My Review:
This is one of the most wild books I have ever read that defies all sorts of storytelling rules and makes me a little annoyed that the author is just willing to come up with any ridiculous mechanism in order to progress the story. Like okay, at one point Kaoru can magically go into the simulated Loop world and relive in entirety the events of the first two books, how convenient!

But, despite it all, I understand that horror requires readers to suspend disbelief, which is why I wrote 'a little annoyed' and not 'a lot annoyed'.

I think I am just more mad at myself for having this mindset of not being able to DNF a book because it was so clear from even the second book that what Suzuki wanted to write is not horror but rather sci-fi/philosophy. So can I even blame him when I was the one who forced myself to finish these two books even though I know I am not that interested in these genres?

I think I'm just trying to ask myself the question, 'do I regret finishing the series?'. And I think the answer is 'no'. Even though this book kind of unraveled the entirety of the first book as just being a simulation and there is literally not even a conclusion of HOW the virus even got introduced into Loop (just some throwaway sentences on how there's always a possibility some outside force maliciously injected some virus in Loop!), I still can't deny that, at the very least, this book is very creative.

Ring is one of my favorite horror books ever, and I still remember the chills I felt when it was revealed that the curse was really a virus, so it's a true testament to how much I loved the first book since it's still influencing my entire perspective on this series to be somewhat positive.
